# GitHub Branch & Commit Conventions

Before suggesting a branch name, commit message, or PR title, detect the repo's existing conventions. Fall back to plugin defaults only when no repo-specific patterns are found.

## Step 1 — Detect repo conventions

Run these checks **before** suggesting any branch/commit/PR format:

```bash
# 1. Check for PR body template
ls .github/pull_request_template.md .github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md 2>/dev/null

# 2. Check for conventional commits config
ls .commitlintrc .commitlintrc.json .commitlintrc.yml .commitlintrc.js 2>/dev/null
cat package.json 2>/dev/null | grep -i "conventional\|commitlint"

# 3. Infer branch prefix patterns from recent PRs
gh pr list --limit 10 --json headRefName --jq '.[].headRefName'
```

- If `.github/pull_request_template.md` exists → use it as the PR body template.
- If commitlint or conventional-changelog config is found → use Conventional Commits format (e.g. `feat(scope): description`).
- If recent PRs share a consistent prefix (e.g. `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`) → reuse that prefix.
- If `config/settings.json` exists in the plugin root → read `defaultBranchPrefix` from it.
- **Fall back to plugin defaults** only when none of the above produce a pattern.

## Step 2 — Plugin defaults (when no pattern found)

| Item | Default |
|------|---------|
| Branch | `codex/<short-description>` |
| Commit | One short present-tense line, e.g. `fix login redirect` |
| PR title | `[codex] <short-description>` |
| PR body | Problem · Cause · Fix · Validation |

## Examples

```bash
# ❌ BAD — generic name ignoring conventions
git checkout -b patch-1

# ✅ GOOD — check for existing patterns first, then apply
gh pr list --limit 5 --json headRefName
# → most branches are "feat/<slug>" → use feat/add-dark-mode
git checkout -b feat/add-dark-mode
```

> Projects can override these defaults by committing any of the convention files above. This rule defers to repo files over plugin defaults.
